<ul>
  <li>Preliminary results from Mexico&rsquo;s National Institute of Statistics and
Geography <a href="http://mexicovoices.blogspot.com/2014/04/mexican-educational-budget-mismanaged.html">indicate massive amounts of fraud</a> in the country&rsquo;s education
system. I can&rsquo;t find credible English sources on this at the moment. See
<a href="http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/primera-plana/2014/impreso/censo-de-sep-confirma-fallas-44861.html">&ldquo;Censo en escuelas descubre anomal√≠as&rdquo;</a> and a campaign to crack down on
this fraud named <a href="http://www.finalabuso.org/">&ldquo;Fin al abuso&rdquo;</a>.</li>
  <li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0375756787/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0375756787&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=blog0cbb-20"><em>The Rise of Theodore Roosevelt</em></a> details Roosevelt&rsquo;s growth from an
awkward, squeaky boy obsessed with taxidermy and books into a man of
staggering power and charisma. Inspiring read. Recommended to me by
<a href="http://www.artofmanliness.com/trunk/1795/some-book-reccomendations-in-honor-of-theodore-roosevelts-birthday/">Art of Manliness</a>.</li>
  <li><a href="http://www.economist.com/news/essays/21600451-finance-not-merely-prone-crises-it-shaped-them-five-historical-crises-show-how-aspects-today-s-fina">&ldquo;The slumps that shaped modern finance&rdquo;</a> covers the history of the
financial industry from the late 18th century forward. Really fascinating
read. (For those reading on a desktop, the web reading interface for this
essay is also pretty nice!)</li>
